# Study prose style

> **Source of truth:** [AGENTS.md](../AGENTS.md) §4. Keep this file in sync when editing.

Applies to every topical study under `Studies/` except `Studies/README.md`.
Reference implementations: [What-Is-Existence.md](../Studies/What-Is-Existence.md)
(ontology exposition, open problems); [Why-Humans-Are-Not-Just-Material.md](../Studies/Why-Humans-Are-Not-Just-Material.md)
(comparative anthropology, critique closings);
[Knowledge-Knower-And-Known.md](../Studies/Knowledge-Knower-And-Known.md) (epistemology,
tradition comparison); [Human-Behavior-And-Society.md](../Studies/Human-Behavior-And-Society.md)
(social philosophy, critique closings).

Write exposition as **continuous scholarly essay**, not as an LLM outline with
visible scaffolding.

## Voice and structure

- **Section openings:** multi-sentence prose that states the position or contrast
  (*Madhyasth Darshan holds…*, *Advaita Vedanta holds…*, *Mainstream science
  answers…*). Do not use `**The claim in one sentence:**`, step tables, or
  per-section Q&A recap tables in exposition (§1–§4).
- **Subsections:** use `### N.M Descriptive title` for argument steps — not
  `### The logic, step by step` with `**Step N —**` bold headers, not
  `**N. Bold title.**` numbered items, and not `#### Argument N:` labels.
- **Between subsections:** one short, content-first bridge when needed (e.g. name
  the next problem). Avoid formulaic tours (`Having examined…`, `To map these…`,
  `the next step is…`, `In short:`).
- **Comparison:** use tables in the dedicated comparison section (typically §4–§5).
  One at-a-glance summary table is enough; do not duplicate recap tables after
  each tradition or label the table `### Comparative Matrix`.
- **Critique:** `### N.1 Tradition — descriptive subtitle` with `**Strengths.**`
  and `**Weaknesses.**` bullet lists (typically §5–§6). End each tradition's
  review with a **plain closing sentence** that names the tradition — not
  `**Verdict:**`, `### Critical assessment`, or `## Critical conclusion`.
- **Section dividers:** do not use `---` horizontal rules between sections
  within the study body.
- **Cross-refs:** `§2.3`, not `Section 2`.

## Do not use

| Pattern | Instead |
|---------|---------|
| `## How to read this study` / tag-legend reader guides | Omit; exposition carries epistemic status without a legend |
| `[Open]`, `[Interpretation]`, `[Text]` bracket tags | Plain prose; unsettled points in an **Open problems** section |
| `**Step N —**` or `**N. Bold title.**` roadmaps | `### N.M Descriptive title` subsections |
| `#### Argument N:` labels | `### N.M Descriptive title` subsections |
| Logical-structure / step-recap tables in exposition | Prose in the comparison or conclusion section only |
| `**Verdict:**` / `### Critical assessment` / `## Critical conclusion` | Plain sentence: *Madhyasth Darshan is best read as…* |
| `honestly`, `honest caveat`, `The honest bottom line` | State the point directly (*What science leaves open*) |
| `On a charitable reading`, `A charitable reading` | State the commitment directly (*Gyan here names…*) |
| `According to this darshan` (for the darshan's own claims) | *Madhyasth Darshan holds…* or state the point in prose |
| `Therefore, the most balanced reading is:` before a closing quote | Plain concluding sentence naming the tradition |
| `**Not constitution.**` elimination headers | Woven prose: *Saturation is not constitution: … Nor is it inherence…* |
| `**Proposed reading:**` / `**Primary reference.**` | *This paper adopts…* / *The relation that fits the texts is…* |
| Subtitle under `#` title (`## A critical writeup…`) | Lead with `**The question:**` and intro paragraph only |
| Meta-signposting (`not decoration`, `prepares its rows`, `keep in view`) | State the substance directly |
| References preamble (`All sources cited in this document…`) | `## References` then tradition subsections |
| `## N. References` (numbered References heading) | `## References` |
| `Linked externally; not stored locally` on entries | External URL in the link; no storage note |
| `one-sentence preview`, `canonical exposition` | Cross-ref the section (`§6.6`) without narrating the document |

## Epistemic honesty without tags or qualifiers

- **Committed readings:** state plainly (*Madhyasth Darshan holds…*, *This paper
  adopts…*, *Advaita Vedanta holds…*). For a genuinely contested fork only,
  use *One reading is…* or *The texts take…* — not `On a charitable reading`.
- **Unsettled points:** name in prose where they arise; collect and argue them in
  an open-problems section (do not label items `[Open]`).
- **Caveats:** state the limitation directly — do not prefix it `honest` or
  `frank`; the reader does not need reminded that you mean it sincerely.
- **Cross-refs:** use when they carry argumentative weight (`§3.3`, `§6.2`), not
  to describe document navigation.

## Terminology

- Pick one running English term per source concept in analytical prose (e.g.
  **Omnipresence** for *satta*), aligned with the glossary and Editorial Notes.
- Block quotes keep the translation’s wording.

## References

- No preamble under `## References`; begin with tradition subsections
  (`### Madhyasth Darshan (primary sources)`, etc.).
- Optional `### Related studies in this collection` for cross-links to other
  studies in the series.
- Each entry: `**TAG** —` author, linked title, optional translator/edition,
  `Cited:` passages. Use `../References/...` for local copies; external URL in
  the link when no local file. Do not append `Linked externally; not stored
  locally` or point readers to `NOT-DOWNLOADED.md` in the study body.
- `Also at <url>` is fine when a local PDF exists and an alternate public URL
  helps; omit when the entry is already an external link only.
- Subsection notes are allowed only when they carry substance (e.g. edition
  numbering for Upanishads), not to explain how the bibliography works.

## Quick check before finishing a study edit

- [ ] No `## How to read this study` or tag legend
- [ ] No `[Open]` / `[Interpretation]` / `[Text]` in the file
- [ ] No `**The claim in one sentence:**`, `**Step N —**`, `**N. Bold title.**`,
  `#### Argument N:`, or `**Verdict:**`
- [ ] No `honestly` / `honest caveat` / `The honest bottom line` / `On a
  charitable reading` / `A charitable reading` qualifiers
- [ ] No `**Not …**` rejection headers in exposition
- [ ] No `### Critical assessment`, `## Critical conclusion`, or `---` section
  dividers in the body
- [ ] No sentences whose only job is to describe section/table layout
- [ ] Comparison tables live in the comparison section, not scattered as recaps
- [ ] Cross-refs use `§`, not `Section`
- [ ] References: `## References` (unnumbered), no section preamble, no
  `Linked externally; not stored locally`
